The presence of functional groups was confirmed by FT-IR spectroscopy (see Fig. 6
                           ). The strong peak at 3321 cm−1 is assigned to the stretching vibration of the OH/NH groups, peaks at 2893 cm−1 and 807 cm-1 are due to the CH stretching and bending vibrations. Strong peaks at 1699, 1687 and 1428 cm−1 are assigned to CO and CC stretching vibration, respectively, other peaks appeared at 1136 and 1095 cm-1 are due to the stretching and bending vibrations of CO bonds in the carboxyl groups. The above investigation suggests the presence of various hydroxyl, carboxylic, carbonyl and amino-containing functional groups on the surface of CQDs derived from organic moieties of Tulsi leaves under hydrothermal condition. Both the methods contain common precursor so the observed peaks are found similar. The observed peaks and data rely on the literature reference (see Table 2
                           ).

Tulsi CQDs are prepared for the application as draw solution in FO experimentation where it will be diluted and exposed in open environment while experimentation. Therefore, it is necessary to check the stability of CQDs solutions using MIC technique (shown in Fig. 7
                           ). Both CQDs were diluted with DI water in different ratios (5 %, 10 %, 15 % and 20 %) to check their antimicrobial property using E. coli bacteria. From the analysis, it was proved that in every ratio, microbial growth took place (Fig. 8
                           A and B). For both types of CQDs i.e., A-1 and R-1, there was no inhibition zone observed even after 12 h of the test. This indicates that any of the concentration is not suitable for open environmental exposure for the experiment.
